Name: Room 237
Review:
The documentary begins with people's experiences of seeing Kubrick's films in theaters and how they knew they were designed to make them think. I think they went wrong when they thought those thoughts have to be figured out.

If anything, Room 237 is a good example of taking things too far and that obsessing over a film maker isn't exactly a healthy thing. There are so many assumptions in this and bending one movie to fit the narrators' theories, it's ridiculous.

I've been meaning to watch this for 7 years, and I can't express how let down I am. Skip.

Name: Live Free or Die Hard
Review: A movie that was released during the time when studios tried to neuter most if not all R rated movies to allow younger audiences to see the movie to drive up ticket sales. Hell, they even cut McClain's iconic catchphrase and covered it with a gun shot sound effect the one time it was said. The unrated cut of this movie undoes these changes and it makes for a pretty good action movie along with all the things you'd expect from a Die Hard movie.

Name: Interstellar
Review: I wont ever forget standing in line to see this in IMAX opening night. Standing there in anticipation with my ticket in hand as I see a group of silent movie goers coming out of the theater from the showing that had just ended with blank looks ‚Äì some with sheer confusion on their face; some with slight smiles and others with teary red eyes . Among them were my parents. I waved at them cheerfully and my mom tried to put into words the experience she had just had but couldn't quite find the words. My dad interrupted her and said "Just let them watch it." "okay, okay. It was really good." That it was. The pure emotion this movie brings out is profound and while usually a 'movie high' wears off within a few days after seeing it for the first time at the cinema, it never quite wore off for this one. It's still my favorite movie to this day.

Don't pass go, don't collect $200. Skip this one. 

Since you accepted spoilers, here goes nothing: It's about a kid who is lonely and sad on an adventure (as the synopsis stated). But it also follows a middle aged man in a panic. By the end of the film you learn it's the little boy, in the future. The film ends with them both holding a little Sonic doll as the boy continues to be lonely, and the man hangs himself with cables in the bathroom. 



Why?

Name: Rainier: A Beer Odyssey
Review:
An incredible and rare look at the mad men era and beyond of the Seattle advertising landscape‚ÄîFollowing Heckler Associates and using Rainier beer as its primary case study this film explores how it became a Washington icon alongside Starbucks and other iconic brands that were also clients of the agency.
